# Character Memory & Reactivity Architecture — "Not Here"

## 1. State Representation: the option space

There are four canonical ways narrative games represent "the game remembers":

### 1a. Boolean flag soup
`lied_to_jonah = true`. Simple, fast, and how most Twine/Ink games ship. Fails at scale: flags carry no metadata (who knows it? when? how bad was it?), so every new reaction requires the writer to remember which flags exist, and "does Mara know?" requires a *second* flag per character per event. Combinatorics explode in the author's head, not in the engine.

### 1b. Raw affinity counters
`mara.trust += 5`. The classic RPG reputation meter. Cheap and legible, but lossy: two players with trust=40 arrived there by completely different histories, and the game can no longer tell them apart. Counters can't produce *specific* callbacks ("you left him at the bridge"), only *generic* tone shifts. Counters as **primary storage** are a dead end for a memory-driven game.

### 1c. Append-only event ledger
Every meaningful thing that happens is appended as an immutable event. Nothing is ever lost; any question ("did the player ever betray anyone in Act 1?") is a query. Perfect fidelity, perfect for retroactive design ("we decided in month 6 that ending C requires never having lied" — with a ledger you can add that check; with flags you can't recover data you never wrote). Cost: queries need an API, and raw events aren't author-friendly.

### 1d. Witnessed-facts model
The key upgrade over a plain ledger: separate **what happened** (facts) from **who knows it** (per-character knowledge sets). This is what makes gossip, secrets, dramatic irony, and a fair-play central mystery *mechanically representable*. The mystery of "Not Here" is literally a set of facts whose knowledge is restricted — the twist reveal is a knowledge-set operation.

### Recommended model: facts + witnesses + derived axes (hybrid of 1c + 1d, with 1b as a *derived cache*)

```ts
// ---------- The ledger: single source of truth, append-only ----------
type CharacterId = "mara" | "jonah" | "edith" | "cole" | "the_visitor";
type Beat = number; // story-time, not wall clock — deterministic & save-friendly

interface Fact {
  id: string;                    // "lied_to_jonah_about_lighthouse_key"
  tags: readonly string[];       // ["deception", "jonah", "act1", "lighthouse", "mystery:door"]
  actor: "player" | CharacterId;
  subject?: CharacterId;         // whom it was done to/about
  severity: number;              // 0..1 emotional magnitude, set by the writer
  valence: number;               // -1..1 (harm .. kindness)
  at: Beat;
  params?: Readonly<Record<string, string | number>>; // for templated callbacks
}

interface Witness {
  factId: string;
  charId: CharacterId;
  source: "saw" | "told" | "inferred" | "confessed";
  fromChar?: CharacterId;        // gossip provenance — enables "Jonah told me."
  learnedAt: Beat;
  distortion: number;            // 0 = accurate; gossip can exaggerate severity
}

interface WorldState {
  readonly facts: ReadonlyArray<Fact>;
  readonly knowledge: ReadonlyArray<Witness>;   // per-character knowledge sets
  readonly beat: Beat;
}

// State transitions return new state — never mutate (engine core is pure,
// shared verbatim by browser and terminal builds).
declare function record(s: WorldState, fact: Fact, witnesses: Witness[]): WorldState;

// ---------- Relationship axes: DERIVED, never stored ----------
type Axis = "trust" | "warmth" | "fear" | "respect";

interface AxisRule {
  when: FactQuery;               // predicate over tags/actor/subject/severity
  axis: Axis;
  delta: number;
  requiresKnowledge: true;       // a character is only affected by facts they KNOW
  halfLifeBeats?: number;        // optional decay → forgiveness is systemic
}

// Pure function; recompute on demand (5 characters × a few hundred facts is trivial).
declare function axes(char: CharacterId, s: WorldState, rules: AxisRule[]): Record<Axis, number>;
```

Why derived-not-stored axes matter: (a) you can rebalance emotional weights in patch 1.1 and every save file retroactively re-derives correct feelings; (b) tooling can answer "why does Mara distrust me?" by listing the contributing facts — CK3-style transparency; (c) it prevents drift bugs where counter and history disagree; (d) it fits the immutability rule and makes the engine trivially replayable/testable (same fact log → same world, always — a golden-log regression suite falls out for free).

Boolean flags don't disappear — they become *queries*: `knows(mara, tagged("deception") & subject("jonah"))`. Same authoring convenience, none of the data loss.

## 2. Making memory VISIBLE — the payoff layer

Memory the player never notices is wasted budget. Four escalating tiers, each cheap-to-expensive:

- **T1 — Callback lines (cheapest, highest volume).** One-off dialogue variants referencing a specific fact, with `params` filling templated details ("You told me it was *locked*, {playerName}."). Rule of thumb: **every severity ≥ 0.5 fact gets at least one T1 callback within the same act** — the "consequence within 15 minutes" rule that makes players trust the game is watching.
- **T2 — Changed greetings & idle behavior.** The first line an NPC says is the single highest-leverage reactive slot in the game (Hades proves this: Hypnos commenting on *how you died* is one line and players cite it constantly). Greetings should be the densest rule set per character.
- **T3 — Gossip propagation.** Knowledge moves between NPCs off-screen. At each scene transition, run a propagation pass: for each (A, B) pair who share the scene, for each fact A knows with a `gossipable` tag, roll against `trust(A→B)` and the fact's juiciness (severity); on success append a `Witness{source:"told", fromChar:A, distortion:…}`. Consequences: the player can *race* the gossip (confess to Jonah before Mara tells him — `source:"confessed"` applies a smaller axis penalty than `"told"`), can trace provenance ("who told you?"), and the world feels alive between visits. This one system generates more emergent drama per line of code than anything else on this list.
- **T4 — Structural consequences.** Scene availability, branch gating, who shows up at the climax, ending eligibility — expressed as fact/knowledge queries over the ledger. Because the ledger is lossless, late-development ending conditions can query *anything* that ever happened.

Also: **memory should be audible.** Character motifs are first-class here — axis-threshold crossings emit music cues (`motif:mara.warm_variant` when warmth crosses 0.6) that the adaptive audio layer consumes in both builds. Undertale's trick wasn't just leitmotif; it was leitmotif *bound to relationship state*.

## 3. Authoring ergonomics — avoiding combinatorial explosion

The proven answer is **salience/specificity-scored rule matching** — Elan Ruskin's Left 4 Dead / "Rule Databases for Contextual Dialog" model (GDC 2012), which Firewatch's walkie system descends from:

```ts
interface DialogRule {
  id: string;
  speaker: CharacterId;
  slot: "greeting" | "callback" | "idle" | "confront" | string;
  criteria: Criterion[];   // predicates over knowledge, axes, scene, beat, stats
  once?: boolean;          // Hades-style: play once, ever
  weight?: number;         // tie-breaker
  line: string;            // may template {fact.params}
}
```

Selection: gather all rules for the current slot whose criteria ALL pass; pick the one with the **most criteria** (most specific wins); tie-break by weight then seeded random; fall through to a zero-criteria generic line that always exists. This is the whole trick against explosion: **writers author only the specific combinations they care about; specificity ranking and guaranteed fallbacks absorb everything else.** Nobody writes the cross-product.

Writer-facing format (compiles to `DialogRule`; keep it flat, greppable, diffable):

```yaml
- speaker: mara
  slot: greeting
  when:
    - mara.knows: { tag: deception, subject: jonah }
    - mara.axes.trust: "< 0.3"
  once: true
  line: "Jonah came by last night. Funny — his version of the key story isn't yours."
```

**Tooling is not optional.** Ship three internal tools early: (1) a **"why this line"** debug overlay showing the winning rule and which criteria beat the runners-up; (2) a **fact-coverage linter** — every authored fact with severity ≥ threshold must be referenced by ≥1 rule, every rule must reference ≥1 reachable fact (catches orphaned memory both directions); (3) a **soak simulator** that plays thousands of random-policy runs through the pure engine and reports unreached rules and axis distributions. The pure-function core makes all three trivial.

### Survey — how the reference games do it

| Game | Mechanism | Steal | Avoid |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Firewatch** | Radio dialog: context + short-term memory of what you told Delilah (lies included), tone tracking; specificity-matched barks descending from the L4D rule DB | Callbacks to *your own words*; letting silence be an input; single-relationship depth | Memory mostly confined to one NPC and one playthrough; little propagation |
| **Hades** | Enormous priority-ordered pool (~21k lines) of one-shot conversations gated by prerequisite predicates (deaths, gifts, story chapter, whom you've met) | The **giant once-only pool + prerequisites** pattern — feels like a mind because it never repeats and always references your actual history; greetings-as-prime-slot | Pure priority list without knowledge modeling — NPCs "know" things they couldn't; fine roguelite-side, wrong for a mystery |
| **Wildermyth** | Events written against abstract **roles** ("a hothead," "someone who lost a limb"); engine casts party members whose traits/history fit; text templates fill specifics | Role-based authoring for the few systemic scenes; history-templated text | Full proceduralism — your cast is authored, not generated |
| **Crusader Kings 3** | Opinion = sum of **timed decaying modifiers each carrying a reason string**; memories fuel content; **secrets are a resource** (knowing one = leverage/hooks) | Transparent derivation ("−20: you imprisoned my brother"), decay-as-forgiveness, secrets-as-currency — directly validates the witnessed-facts model | Numeric-first presentation; "Not Here" should surface reasons through dialogue, not tooltips (though the debug build should absolutely have the tooltip) |

## 4. Cast design for a 4–6 ensemble

**Contrast matrix.** Build a table: characters × {want, need, relationship-to-the-mystery, default stance toward player, temperament, social role}. Enforce: every pair differs on ≥2 columns, and no two characters share the same *function* in a scene (if two people would give the same advice, cut or merge one). Five is the sweet spot: enough for triangulated gossip, small enough that every character can be deeply rule-covered.

**One motif per character, mechanically bound.** Each character owns a leitmotif that is (a) their audio identity in both builds (full arrangement in browser, chip/tracker reduction in terminal), (b) *state-reactive*: mode/instrumentation variants keyed to relationship-axis bands, and (c) a mystery instrument — motif fragments appearing where they "shouldn't" are legitimate fair-play clues (Undertale's deepest trick: the twist is audible before it's sayable).

**Interlocking secrets.** Each character holds exactly one shard of the central mystery, and each shard is *personally costly* to that character — so extraction is character drama, not exposition. Design constraint: **any 3 of 5 shards suffice to infer the twist**, so multiple social paths reach the truth and no single NPC is a mandatory key. In the model, shards are just facts with restricted initial knowledge sets and `gossipable: false` — the twist is engine-native, and "who knew what, when" is queryable for the post-reveal recontextualization pass (each character gets reaction rules keyed to `player.knows(shard_*)`).

**Stats hook.** Player stats gate *fact creation and witnessing*: high Perception adds you as witness to facts that otherwise happen unobserved; high Empathy unlocks `confessed`-source options; etc. Different builds literally know different worlds → replay pull. The LLM-assisted character-creation moment maps a free-text self-description onto stats + 2–3 seed facts/tags (deterministic engine remains sole authority afterward — LLM writes *into* the fact schema once, then exits).

## 5. Sizing & engine notes

- 5 characters × ~300 reachable facts/run × derived axes = microseconds; recompute everything, cache nothing until profiling says otherwise.
- Save file = `{facts, knowledge, beat, rngSeed}` — a few KB of JSON, identical across web (localStorage/IndexedDB) and terminal (file). Old saves survive rule rebalancing because feelings are re-derived.
- The whole system is one pure TypeScript module with zero platform dependencies — it slots cleanly under both renderers, and the seeded selection makes bug reports reproducible from a save file alone.
